# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: home-energy-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:home-energy-management/demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Conventional power stations, such as coal-fired, gas, and nuclear powered plants, as well as hydroelectric dams and large-scale solar power stations, are centralized and often require electric energy to be transmitted over long distances.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] By contrast, DER systems are decentralized, modular, and more flexible technologies that are located close to the load they serve, albeit having capacities of only 10 megawatts (MW) or less.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] These systems can comprise multiple generation and storage components; in this instance, they are referred to as hybrid power systems.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] DER systems typically use renewable energy sources, including small hydro, biomass, biogas, solar power, wind power, and geothermal power, and increasingly play an important role for the electric power distribution system.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A grid-connected device for electricity storage can also be classified as a DER system and is often called a **distributed energy storage system** (**DESS**).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] By means of an interface, DER systems can be managed and coordinated within a smart grid.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed generation and storage enables the collection of energy from many sources and may lower environmental impacts and improve the security of supply.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] One of the major issues with the integration of the DER such as solar power, wind power, etc. is the uncertain nature of such electricity resources.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Microgrids are modern, localized, small-scale grids, contrary to the traditional, centralized electricity grid (macrogrid).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Microgrids can disconnect from the centralized grid and operate autonomously, strengthen grid resilience, and help mitigate grid disturbances.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] They are typically low-voltage AC grids, often use diesel generators, and are installed by the community they serve.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Microgrids increasingly employ a mixture of different distributed energy resources, such as solar hybrid power systems, which significantly reduce the amount of carbon emitted.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Historically, central plants have been an integral part of the electric grid, in which large generating facilities are specifically located either close to resources or otherwise located far from populated load centers.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] These, in turn, supply the traditional transmission and distribution (T&D) grid that distributes bulk power to load centers and from there to consumers.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] These were developed when the costs of transporting fuel and integrating generating technologies into populated areas far exceeded the cost of developing T&D facilities and tariffs.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Central plants are usually designed to take advantage of available economies of scale in a site-specific manner, and are built as "one-off", custom projects.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Thus, the grid had become the main driver of remote customers' power costs and power quality problems, which became more acute as digital equipment required extremely reliable electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Efficiency gains no longer come from increasing generating capacity, but from smaller units located closer to sites of demand.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For example, coal power plants are built away from cities to prevent their heavy air pollution from affecting the populace.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In addition, such plants are often built near collieries to minimize the cost of transporting coal.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Hydroelectric plants are by their nature limited to operating at sites with sufficient water flow.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Low pollution is a crucial advantage of combined cycle plants that burn natural gas.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The low pollution permits the plants to be near enough to a city to provide district heating and cooling.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resources are mass-produced, small, and less site-specific.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Along with higher relative prices for energy, higher overall complexity and total costs for regulatory oversight, tariff administration, and metering and billing.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Capital markets have come to realize that right-sized resources, for individual customers, distribution substations, or microgrids, are able to offer important but little-known economic advantages over central plants.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Smaller units achieved greater economic benefits through mass-production than larger units gained from their size alone.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The increased value of these resources—resulting from improvements in financial risk, engineering flexibility, security, and environmental quality—often outweighs their apparent cost disadvantages.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed generation (DG), vis-à-vis central plants, must be justified on a life-cycle basis.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Unfortunately, many of the direct, and virtually all of the indirect, benefits of DG are not captured within traditional utility cash-flow accounting.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] While the levelized cost of DG is typically more expensive than conventional, centralized sources on a kilowatt-hour basis, this does not consider negative aspects of conventional fuels.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The additional premium for DG is rapidly declining as demand increases and technology progresses, and sufficient and reliable demand may bring economies of scale, innovation, competition, and more flexible financing, that could make DG clean energy part of a more diversified future.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] DG reduces the amount of energy lost in transmitting electricity because the electricity is generated very near where it is used, perhaps even in the same building.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This also reduces the size and number of power lines that must be constructed.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Typical DER systems in a feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme have low maintenance, low pollution and high efficiencies.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In the past, these traits required dedicated operating engineers and large complex plants to reduce pollution.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] However, modern embedded systems can provide these traits with automated operation and renewable energy, such as solar, wind and geothermal.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This reduces the size of power plant that can show a profit.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In November 2024 Deye and Sol-Ark inverter manufacturer remotely disabled in some countries due to alleged regional sales policy dispute.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The companies later claimed the blockage was not remote but due to geofencing mechanisms built into the inverters.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] EU NIS2 directive expands the cybersecurity requirements to the energy generation market, which has faced backlash from renewable energy lobby groups.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Grid parity occurs when an alternative energy source can generate electricity at a levelized cost (LCOE) that is less than or equal to the end consumer's retail price.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Reaching grid parity is considered to be the point at which an energy source becomes a contender for widespread development without subsidies or government support.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Since the 2010s, grid parity for solar and wind has become a reality in a growing number of markets, including Australia, several European countries, and some states in the U.S.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed energy resource (**DER**) systems are small-scale power generation or storage technologies (typically in the range of 1 kW to 10,000 kW) used to provide an alternative to or an enhancement of the traditional electric power system.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] DER systems typically are characterized by high initial capital costs per kilowatt.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] DER systems also serve as storage device and are often called *Distributed energy storage systems* (DESS).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed cogeneration sources use steam turbines, natural gas-fired fuel cells, microturbines or reciprocating engines to turn generators.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The hot exhaust is then used for space or water heating, or to drive an absorptive chiller for cooling such as air-conditioning.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In addition to natural gas-based schemes, distributed energy projects can also include other renewable or low carbon fuels including biofuels, biogas, landfill gas, sewage gas, coal bed methane, syngas and associated petroleum gas.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Delta-ee consultants stated in 2013 that with 64% of global sales, the fuel cell micro combined heat and power passed the conventional systems in sales in 2012.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] 20.000 units were sold in Japan in 2012 overall within the Ene Farm project.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] With a Lifetime of around 60,000 hours for PEM fuel cell units, which shut down at night, this equates to an estimated lifetime of between ten and fifteen years.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For a price of $22,600 before installation.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For 2013 a state subsidy for 50,000 units is in place.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In addition, molten carbonate fuel cell and solid oxide fuel cells using natural gas, such as the ones from FuelCell Energy and the Bloom energy server, or waste-to-energy processes such as the Gate 5 Energy System are used as a distributed energy resource.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Photovoltaics uses solar cells assembled into solar panels to convert sunlight into electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] It is a growing technology, doubling its worldwide installed capacity every couple of years.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] PV systems range from distributed, residential, and commercial rooftop or building integrated installations, to large, centralized utility-scale photovoltaic power stations.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The predominant PV technology is crystalline silicon, while thin-film solar cell technology accounts for about 10 percent of global photovoltaic deployment.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In recent years, PV technology has improved its sunlight to electricity conversion efficiency, reduced the installation cost per watt as well as its energy payback time (EPBT) and levelised cost of electricity (LCOE), and has reached grid parity in at least 19 different markets in 2014.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] As most renewable energy sources and unlike coal and nuclear, solar PV is variable and non-dispatchable, but has no fuel costs, operating pollution, as well as greatly reduced mining-safety and operating-safety issues.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] It produces peak power around local noon each day and its capacity factor is around 20 percent.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Wind turbines can be distributed energy resources or they can be built at utility scale.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] These have low maintenance and low pollution, but distributed wind unlike utility-scale wind has much higher costs than other sources of energy.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] As with solar, wind energy is variable and non-dispatchable.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Wind towers and generators have substantial insurable liabilities caused by high winds, but good operating safety.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed generation from wind hybrid power systems combines wind power with other DER systems.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] One such example is the integration of wind turbines into solar hybrid power systems, as wind tends to complement solar because the peak operating times for each system occur at different times of the day and year.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Hydroelectricity is the most widely used form of renewable energy and its potential has already been explored to a large extent or is compromised due to issues such as environmental impacts on fisheries, and increased demand for recreational access.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] However, using modern 21st century technology, such as wave power, can make large amounts of new hydropower capacity available, with minor environmental impact.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Modular and scalable *Next generation kinetic energy turbines* can be deployed in arrays to serve the needs on a residential, commercial, industrial, municipal or even regional scale.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] *Microhydro kinetic generators* neither require dams nor impoundments, as they utilize the kinetic energy of water motion, either waves or flow.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] No construction is needed on the shoreline or sea bed, which minimizes environmental impacts to habitats and simplifies the permitting process.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Such power generation also has minimal environmental impact and non-traditional microhydro applications can be tethered to existing construction such as docks, piers, bridge abutments, or similar structures.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Municipal solid waste (MSW) and natural waste, such as sewage sludge, food waste and animal manure will decompose and discharge methane-containing gas that can be collected and used as fuel in gas turbines or micro turbines to produce electricity as a distributed energy resource.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Additionally, a California-based company, Gate 5 Energy Partners, Inc. has developed a process that transforms natural waste materials, such as sewage sludge, into biofuel that can be combusted to power a steam turbine that produces power.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This power can be used in lieu of grid-power at the waste source (such as a treatment plant, farm or dairy).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A distributed energy resource is not limited to the generation of electricity but may also include a device to store distributed energy (DE).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Distributed energy storage systems (DESS) applications include several types of battery, pumped hydro, compressed air, and thermal energy storage.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Access to energy storage for commercial applications is easily accessible through programs such as energy storage as a service (ESaaS).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Compared to the other types, lead-acid batteries have a shorter lifetime and lower energy density.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] (4–6% per year) as well as low investment and maintenance costs, they are currently the predominant technology used in small-scale, residential PV systems, as lithium-ion batteries are still being developed and about 3.5 times as expensive as lead-acid batteries.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] may serve as future storage devices, since most vehicles are parked an average of 95 percent of the time, their batteries could be used to let electricity flow from the car to the power lines and back.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] ) to a very high speed of about 20,000 to over 50,000 rpm in a vacuum enclosure.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Flywheels can respond quickly as they store and feed back electricity into the grid in a matter of seconds.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For reasons of reliability, distributed generation resources would be interconnected to the same transmission grid as central stations.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Various technical and economic issues occur in the integration of these resources into a grid.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Technical problems arise in the areas of power quality, voltage stability, harmonics, reliability, protection, and control.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Behavior of protective devices on the grid must be examined for all combinations of distributed and central station generation.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A large scale deployment of distributed generation may affect grid-wide functions such as frequency control and allocation of reserves.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] As a result, smart grid functions, virtual power plants and grid energy storage such as power to gas stations are added to the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Conflicts occur between utilities and resource managing organizations.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Each distributed generation resource has its own integration issues.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Solar PV and wind power both have intermittent and unpredictable generation, so they create many stability issues for voltage and frequency.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] These voltage issues affect mechanical grid equipment, such as load tap changers, which respond too often and wear out much more quickly than utilities anticipated.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Also, without any form of energy storage during times of high solar generation, companies must rapidly increase generation around the time of sunset to compensate for the loss of solar generation.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This high ramp rate produces what the industry terms the *duck curve* that is a major concern for grid operators in the future.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Storage can fix these issues if it can be implemented.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Flywheels have shown to provide excellent frequency regulation.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Also, flywheels are highly cyclable compared to batteries, meaning they maintain the same energy and power after a significant amount of cycles( on the order of 10,000 cycles).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Short term use batteries, at a large enough scale of use, can help to flatten the duck curve and prevent generator use fluctuation and can help to maintain voltage profile.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] However, cost is a major limiting factor for energy storage as each technique is prohibitively expensive to produce at scale and comparatively not energy dense compared to liquid fossil fuels.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Finally, another method of aiding in integration is in the use of intelligent inverters that have the capability to also store the energy when there is more energy production than consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] There have been some efforts to mitigate voltage and frequency issues due to increased implementation of DG.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Most notably, IEEE 1547 sets the standard for interconnection and interoperability of distributed energy resources.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] IEEE 1547 sets specific curves signaling when to clear a fault as a function of the time after the disturbance and the magnitude of the voltage irregularity or frequency irregularity.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Voltage issues also give legacy equipment the opportunity to perform new operations.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Notably, inverters can regulate the voltage output of DGs.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Changing inverter impedances can change voltage fluctuations of DG, meaning inverters have the ability to control DG voltage output.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] To reduce the effect of DG integration on mechanical grid equipment, transformers and load tap changers have the potential to implement specific tap operation vs. voltage operation curves mitigating the effect of voltage irregularities due to DG.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] That is, load tap changers respond to voltage fluctuations that last for a longer period than voltage fluctuations created from DG equipment.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] It is now possible to combine technologies such as photovoltaics, batteries and cogeneration to make stand alone distributed generation systems.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Recent work has shown that such systems have a low levelized cost of electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Many authors now think that these technologies may enable a mass-scale grid defection because consumers can produce electricity using off grid systems primarily made up of solar photovoltaic technology.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For example, the Rocky Mountain Institute has proposed that there may wide scale grid defection.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This is backed up by studies in the Midwest.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Cogenerators find favor because most buildings already burn fuels, and the cogeneration can extract more value from the fuel.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Local production has no electricity transmission losses on long distance power lines or energy losses from the Joule effect in transformers where in general 8-15% of the energy is lost (see also cost of electricity by source).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Some larger installations utilize combined cycle generation.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Usually this consists of a gas turbine whose exhaust boils water for a steam turbine in a Rankine cycle.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The condenser of the steam cycle provides the heat for space heating or an absorptive chiller.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Combined cycle plants with cogeneration have the highest known thermal efficiencies, often exceeding 85%.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In countries with high pressure gas distribution, small turbines can be used to bring the gas pressure to domestic levels whilst extracting useful energy.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] If the UK were to implement this countrywide an additional 2-4 GWe would become available.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A *microgrid* is a localized grouping of electricity generation, energy storage, and loads that normally operates connected to a traditional centralized grid (macrogrid).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This single point of common coupling with the macrogrid can be disconnected.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The microgrid can then function autonomously.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Generation and loads in a microgrid are usually interconnected at low voltage and it can operate in DC, AC, or the combination of both.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] From the point of view of the grid operator, a connected microgrid can be controlled as if it were one entity.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Microgrid generation resources can include stationary batteries, fuel cells, solar, wind, or other energy sources.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The multiple dispersed generation sources and ability to isolate the microgrid from a larger network would provide highly reliable electric power.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Produced heat from generation sources such as microturbines could be used for local process heating or space heating, allowing flexible trade off between the needs for heat and electric power.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Micro-grids have seen implementation in a number of communities over the world.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] For example, Tesla has implemented a solar micro-grid in the Samoan island of Ta'u, powering the entire island with solar energy.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This localized production system has helped save over 380 cubic metres (100,000 US gal) of diesel fuel.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] It is also able to sustain the island for three whole days if the sun were not to shine at all during that period.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] This is a great example of how micro-grid systems can be implemented in communities to encourage renewable resource usage and localized production.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] To plan and install Microgrids correctly, engineering modelling is needed.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Multiple simulation tools and optimization tools exist to model the economic and electric effects of Microgrids.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A widely used economic optimization tool is the Distributed Energy Resources Customer Adoption Model (DER-CAM) from Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] Another frequently used commercial economic modelling tool is Homer Energy, originally designed by the National Renewable Laboratory.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] There are also some power flow and electrical design tools guiding the Microgrid developers.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The Pacific Northwest National Laboratory designed the public available GridLAB-D tool and the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) designed OpenDSS to simulate the distribution system (for Microgrids).
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A professional integrated DER-CAM and OpenDSS version is available via BankableEnergy Archived 11 July 2018 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] A European tool that can be used for electrical, cooling, heating, and process heat demand simulation is EnergyPLAN from the Aalborg University, Denmark.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] In 2010 Colorado enacted a law requiring that by 2020 that 3% of the power generated in Colorado utilize distributed generation of some sort.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] On 11 October 2017, California Governor Jerry Brown signed into law a bill, SB 338, that makes utility companies plan "carbon-free alternatives to gas generation" in order to meet peak demand.
[src:home-energy-management/distributed-generation] The law requires utilities to evaluate issues such as energy storage, efficiency, and distributed energy resources.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Green engineering practices improve the life cycle of the components of machines which convert energy from one form into another.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Observing appliance usage, establishing an energy usage profile, and revealing energy consumption patterns in circumstances where energy is used poorly, can pinpoint user habits and behaviors in energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Appliance energy profiling helps identify inefficient appliances with high energy consumption and energy load.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Seasonal variations also greatly influence energy load, as more air-conditioning is used in warmer seasons and heating in colder seasons.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Achieving a balance between energy load and user comfort is complex yet essential for energy preservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] On a large scale, a few factors affect energy consumption trends, including political issues, technological developments, economic growth, and environmental concerns.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] User behavior has a significant effect on energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It involves user activity detection, profiling, and appliance interaction behaviors.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] User profiling consists of the identification of energy usage patterns of the user and replacing required system settings with automated settings that can be initiated on request.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Within user profiling, personal characteristics are instrumental in affecting energy conservation behavior.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These characteristics include household income, education, gender, age, and social norms.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] User behavior also relies on the impact of personality traits, social norms, and attitudes on energy conservation behavior.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Beliefs and attitudes toward a convenient lifestyle, environmentally friendly transport, energy security, and residential location choices affect energy conservation behavior.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, energy conservation can be made possible by adopting pro-environmental behavior and energy-efficient systems.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Education on approaches to energy conservation can result in wise energy use.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The choices made by the users yield energy usage patterns.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Rigorous analysis of these usage patterns identifies waste energy patterns, and improving those patterns may reduce significant energy load.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Therefore, human behavior is critical to determining the implications of energy conservation measures and solving environmental problems.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Substantial energy conservation may be achieved if users' habit loops are modified.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] User habits significantly impact energy demand; thus, providing recommendations for improving user habits contributes to energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Micro-moments are essential in realizing energy consumption patterns and are identified using a variety of sensing units positioned in prominent areas across the home.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The micro-moment is an event that changes the state of the appliance from inactive to active and helps in building users' energy consumption profiles according to their activities.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation can be achieved through user habits by following energy-saving recommendations at micro-moments.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Unnecessary energy usage can be decreased by selecting a suitable schedule for appliance operation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Creating an effective scheduling system requires an understanding of user habits regarding appliances.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Many techniques for energy conservation comprise off-peak scheduling, which means operating an appliance in a low-price energy hour.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This schedule can be achieved after user habits regarding appliance use are understood.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Most energy providers divide the energy tariff into high and low-price hours; therefore, scheduling an appliance to work an off-peak hour will significantly reduce electricity bills.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] User activity detection leads to the precise detection of appliances required for an activity.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] If an appliance is active but not required for a user's current activity, it wastes energy and can be turned off to conserve energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The precise identification of user activities is necessary to achieve this method of energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation measures have primarily focused on technological innovations to improve efficiencies and financial incentives with theoretical explanations obtained from the mentioned analytical traditions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Existing buildings can improve energy efficiency by changing structural maintenance materials, adjusting the composition of air conditioning systems, selecting energy-saving equipment, and formulating subsidy policies.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These measures can improve users' thermal comfort and reduce buildings' environmental impact.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The selection of combinatorial optimization schemes that contain measures to guide and restrict users' behavior in addition to carrying out demand-side management can dynamically adjust energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] At the same time, economic means should enable users to change their behavior and achieve a low-carbon life.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Combination optimization and pricing incentives reduce building energy consumption and carbon emissions and reduce users' costs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Monitoring through energy audits can help in achieving energy efficiency in existing buildings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] An energy audit is an inspection and analysis of energy use in a system intending to reduce energy input without negatively affecting output.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy audits can determine specific opportunities for energy conservation and efficiency measures as well as determine cost-effective strategies.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Training professionals typically accomplish this and can be part of some national programs discussed above.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Smartphone apps enables homeowners to complete relatively sophisticated energy audits themselves.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] For instance, smart thermostats can connect to standard HVAC systems to maintain energy-saving indoor temperatures.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In addition, data loggers can also be installed to monitor the interior temperature and humidity levels to provide a more precise understanding of the conditions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] If the data gathered is compared with the users' perceptions of comfort, more fine-tuning of the interiors can be implemented (e.g., increasing the temperature where A.C. is used to prevent over-cooling).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Building technologies and smart meters can allow commercial and residential energy users to visualize the impact their energy use can have in their workplaces or homes.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Advanced real-time energy metering can help people save energy through their actions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Another approach towards energy conservation is the implementation of ECMs in commercial buildings, which often employ Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) experienced in energy performance contracting.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This industry has been around since the 1970s and is more prevalent than ever today.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The US-based organization EVO (Efficiency Valuation Organization) has created a set of guidelines for ESCOs to adhere to in evaluating the savings achieved by ECMs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These guidelines are called the International Performance Measurement and Verification Protocol (IPMVP).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy efficiency can also be achieved by upgrading certain aspects of existing buildings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Making thermal improvements by adding insulation to crawl spaces and ensuring no leaks achieves an efficient building envelope, reducing the need for mechanical systems to heat and cool the space.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] High-performance insulation is also supported by adding double/triple-glazed windows to minimize heat transmission.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] A window windcatcher can reduce the total energy use of a building by 23.3%.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Paint colors and new paint technologies can conserve energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation through users' behaviors requires understanding household occupants' lifestyle, social, and behavioral factors in analyzing energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Replacing existing appliances with newer and more efficient ones leads to energy efficiency as less energy is wasted throughout.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Overall, energy efficiency behaviors are identified more with one-time, cost-incurring investments in efficient appliances and retrofits, while energy curtailment behaviors include repetitive, low-cost energy-saving efforts.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] To identify and optimize residential energy use, conventional and behavioral economics, technology adoption theory and attitude-based decision-making, social and environmental psychology, and sociology must be analyzed.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The techno-economic and psychological literature analysis focuses on the individual attitude, behavior, and choice/context/external conditions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In contrast, the sociological literature relies more on the energy consumption practices shaped by the social, cultural, and economic factors in a dynamic setting.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Many steps can be taken toward energy conservation and efficiency when designing new buildings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In passive solar building designs, windows, walls, and floors are made to collect, store, and distribute solar energy in the form of heat in the winter and reject solar heat in the summer.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The key to designing a passive solar building is to best take advantage of the local climate.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Elements to be considered include window placement and glazing type, thermal insulation, thermal mass, and shading.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Optimizing daylighting can decrease energy waste from incandescent bulbs, windows, and balconies, allow natural ventilation, reduce the need for heating and cooling, low flow mixers aid in water conservation, and upgrade to Energy star rated appliances consume less energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Designing a building according to LEED guidelines while incorporating smart home technology can help save a lot of energy and money in the long run.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Passive solar design techniques can be applied most easily to new buildings, but existing buildings can be retrofitted.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Mainly, energy conservation is achieved by modifying user habits or providing an energy-saving recommendation of curtailing an appliance or scheduling it to low-price energy tariff hours.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Besides changing user habits and appliance control, identifying irrelevant appliances concerning user activities in smart homes saves energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Smart home technology can advise users on energy-saving strategies according to their behavior, encouraging behavioral change that leads to energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This guidance includes reminders to turn off lights, leakage sensors to prevent plumbing issues, running appliances on off-peak hours, and smart sensors that save energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Such technology learns user-appliance activity patterns, gives a complete overview of various energy-consuming appliances, and can provide guidance to improve these patterns to contribute to energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It can strategically schedule appliances to the energy-efficient mode, or plan to work during off-peak hours.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This usually leads to appliance curtailment in which an appliance is either scheduled to work another time or is turned off.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Appliance curtailment involves appliance recognition, activity-appliances model, unattended appliance detection, and energy conservation service.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The appliance recognition module detects active appliances to identify the activities of smart home users.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] After identifying users' activities, the association between the functional appliances and user activities is established.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The unattended appliance detection module looks for active appliances but is unrelated to user activity.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These functional appliances waste energy and can be turned off by providing recommendations to the user.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Users can give weight to certain appliances that increase user comfort while conserving energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy consumption models of energy consumption of appliances and the level of comfort they create can balance priorities among smart home comfort levels and energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] According to Kashimoto, Ogura, Yamamoto, Yasumoto, and Ito, the energy supply reduces based on the historical state of the appliance and increases according to the comfort level requirement of the user, leading to a targeted energy-saving ratio.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Scenarios-based energy consumption can be employed as a strategy for energy conservation, with each scenario encompassing a specific set of rules for energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Transporting people, goods, and services represented 29% of U.S. energy consumption in 2007.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The transportation sector also accounted for about 33% of U.S. carbon dioxide emissions in 2006, with highway vehicles accounting for about 84% of that, making transportation an essential target for addressing global climate change (E.I.A., 2008).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Land is developing at a faster rate than population growth, leading to urban sprawl and, therefore, high transportation energy intensity as more people need to commute longer distances to jobs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, the location of a building is essential in decreasing embodied emissions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In transportation, state and local efforts in energy conservation and efficiency measures tend to be more targeted and smaller in scale.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Zoning reforms that allow greater urban density and designs for walking and bicycling can greatly reduce energy consumed for transportation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Many Americans work in jobs that allow for remote work instead of commuting daily, which is a significant opportunity to conserve energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Intelligent transportation systems (ITS) provide a solution to traffic congestion and C.E.s caused by increased vehicles.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] ITS combines improvements in information technology and systems, communications, sensors, controllers, and advanced mathematical methods with the traditional world of transportation infrastructure.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It improves traffic safety and mobility, reduces environmental impact, promotes sustainable transportation, and increases productivity.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] ITS can strengthen connection and cooperation between people, vehicles, roads, and the environment while improving road capacity, reducing traffic accidents, and improving transportation efficiency and safety by alleviating traffic congestion and reducing pollution.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It makes full use of traffic information as an application service, which can enhance the operational efficiency of existing traffic facilities.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The most significant energy-saving potential is that there are the most problems in urban transportation in various countries, such as management systems, policies and regulations, planning, technology, operation, and management mechanism.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Improvements in one or several aspects will improve road transportation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Efficiency has a positive impact, which leads to the improvement of the urban traffic environment and efficiency.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In addition to ITS, transit-oriented development (T.O.D.) improves transportation in urban areas by emphasizing density, proximity to transit, diversity of uses, and streetscape design.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Density is important for optimizing location and is a way to cut down on driving.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Planners can regulate development rights by exchanging them from ecologically sensitive areas to growth-friendly zones according to density transfer procedures.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Distance is defined as the accessibility of rail and bus transits, which serve as deterrents for driving.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] For transit-oriented development to be feasible, transportation stops must be close to where people live.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Diversity refers to mixed-use areas that offer essential services close to homes and offices and include residential spaces for different socioeconomic categories, commercial and retail.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This creates a pedestrian shed where one area can meet people's everyday needs on foot.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Lastly, the streetscapes design involves minimal parking and walkable areas that calm traffic.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Generous parking incentivizes people to use cars, whereas minimal and expensive parking deters commuters.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] At the same time, streetscapes can be designed to incorporate bicycling lanes and designated bicycle paths and trails.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] People may commute by bicycle without being concerned about their bicycles becoming wet because of covered bicycle storage.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This encourages commuters to use bicycles rather than other modes of transportation and contributes to energy saving.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] People will be happy to walk a few blocks from a train stop if there are attractive, pedestrian-friendly outdoor spaces nearby with good lighting, park benches, outdoor tables at cafés, shade tree plantings, pedestrian courts that are blocked off to cars, and public internet connection.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Additionally, this strategy calms traffic, improving the intended pedestrian environment.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] New urban planning schemes can be designed to improve connectivity in cities through networks of interconnected streets that spread out traffic flow, slow down vehicles, and make walking more pleasant.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] By dividing the number of road links by the number of road nodes, the connectivity index is calculated.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The higher the connectivity index, the greater the route choices and the better the pedestrian access.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Realizing the transportation impacts associated with buildings allows commuters to take steps toward energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Connectivity encourages energy-conserving behaviors as commuters use fewer cars, walk and bike more, and use public transportation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] For commuters who do not have the option of public transportation, smaller vehicles that are hybrid or have better mileage can be used.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Homeowners implementing ECMs in their residential buildings often start with an energy audit.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This is a way homeowners look at what areas of their homes are using, and possibly losing energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Residential energy auditors are accredited by the Building Performance Institute (BPI) or the Residential Energy Services Network (RESNET).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Homeowners can hire a professional or do it themselves or use a smartphone to help do an audit.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation measures are often combined into larger guaranteed Energy Savings Performance Contracts to maximize energy savings while minimizing disruption to building occupants by coordinating renovations.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Some ECMs cost less to implement yet return higher energy savings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Traditionally, lighting projects were a good example of "low hanging fruit" that could be used to drive implementation of more substantial upgrades to HVAC systems in large facilities.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Smaller buildings might combine window replacement with modern insulation using advanced building foams to improve energy for performance.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy dashboard projects are a new kind of ECM that relies on the behavioral change of building occupants to save energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] When implemented as part of a program, case studies, such as that for the DC Schools, report energy savings up 30%.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Under the right circumstances, open energy dashboards can even be implemented for free to improve upon these savings even more.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Consumers are often poorly informed of the savings of energy-efficient products.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] A prominent example of this is the energy savings that can be made by replacing an incandescent light bulb with a more modern alternative.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] When purchasing light bulbs, many consumers opt for cheap incandescent bulbs, failing to take into account their higher energy costs and lower lifespans when compared to modern compact fluorescent and LED bulbs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Although these energy-efficient alternatives have a higher upfront cost, their long lifespan and low energy use can save consumers a considerable amount of money.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The price of LED bulbs has also been steadily decreasing in the past five years due to improvements in semiconductor technology.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Many LED bulbs on the market qualify for utility rebates that further reduce the price of the purchase to the consumer.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Department of Energy state that widespread adoption of LED lighting over the next 20 years could result in about $265 billion worth of savings in United States energy costs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The research one must put into conserving energy is often too time-consuming and costly for the average consumer when there are cheaper products and technology available using today's fossil fuels.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Some governments and NGOs are attempting to reduce this complexity with Eco-labels that make differences in energy efficiency easy to research while shopping.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] To provide the kind of information and support people need to invest money, time and effort in energy conservation, it is important to understand and link to people's topical concerns.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] For instance, some retailers argue that bright lighting stimulates purchasing.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] However, health studies have demonstrated that headache, stress, blood pressure, fatigue and worker error all generally increase with the common over-illumination present in many workplace and retail settings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It has been shown that natural daylighting increases productivity levels of workers, while reducing energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In warm climates where air conditioning is used, any household device that gives off heat will result in a larger load on the cooling system.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Items such as stoves, dishwashers, clothes dryers, hot water, and incandescent lighting all add heat to the home.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Low-power or insulated versions of these devices give off less heat for the air conditioning to remove.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The air conditioning system can also improve efficiency by using a heat sink that is cooler than the standard air heat exchanger, such as geothermal or water.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In cold climates, heating air and water is a major demand for household energy use.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Significant energy reductions are possible by using different technologies.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Heat pumps are a more efficient alternative to electrical resistance heaters for warming air or water.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] A variety of efficient clothes dryers are available, and the clothes lines requires no energy- only time.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Natural-gas (or bio-gas) condensing boilers and hot-air furnaces increase efficiency over standard hot-flue models.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Standard electric boilers can be made to run only at hours of the day when they are needed by means of a time switch.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In showers, a semi-closed-loop system could be used.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] New construction implementing heat exchangers can capture heat from wastewater or exhaust air in bathrooms, laundry, and kitchens.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In both warm and cold climate extremes, airtight thermal insulated construction is the largest factor determining the efficiency of a home.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Insulation is added to minimize the flow of heat to or from the home, but can be labor-intensive to retrofit to an existing home.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Although energy efficiency is expected to play a vital role in cost-effectively cutting energy demand, only a small part of its economic potential is exploited in Asia.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Governments have implemented a range of subsidies such as cash grants, cheap credit, tax exemptions, and co-financing with public-sector funds to encourage energy-efficiency initiatives across several sectors.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Road transportation is the highest priority to achieve energy conservation effectively and reduce emissions, particularly since social and economic development has entered the "new norm" period.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Generally speaking, the government should make comprehensive plans for conservation and emissions reduction in the road transportation industry within the three dimensions of demand, structure, and technology.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] For example, encouraging trips using public transportation and new transportation modes such as car-sharing and increasing investment in new energy vehicles in structure reform, etc.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] At the end of 2006, the European Union (EU) pledged to cut its annual consumption of primary energy by 20% by 2020.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The EU Energy Efficiency Directive 2012 mandates energy efficiency improvements within the EU.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] As part of the EU's SAVE program, aimed at promoting energy efficiency and encouraging energy-saving behavior, the Boiler Efficiency Directive specifies minimum levels of efficiency for boilers using liquid or gaseous fuels.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] There is steady progress on energy regulation implementation in Europe, North America, and Asia, with the highest number of building energy standards being adopted and implemented.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Moreover, the performance of Europe is highly encouraging concerning energy standard activities.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] They recorded the highest percentage of mandatory energy standards compared to the other five regions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In 2050, energy savings in Europe can reach 67% of the 2019 baseline scenario, amounting to a demand of 361 Mtoe in an "energy efficiency first" societal trend scenario.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] A condition is that there be no rebound effect, for otherwise the savings are 32% only or energy use may even increase by 42% if techno-economic potentials are not realized.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Germany has reduced its primary energy consumption by 11% from 1990 to 2015 and set itself goals of reducing it by 30% by the year 2030 and by 50% by the year 2050 in comparison to the level of 2008.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Petroleum Conservation Research Association (PCRA) is an Indian governmental body created in 1978 that engages in promoting energy efficiency and conservation in every walk of life.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In the recent past, PCRA has organised mass media campaigns in television, radio, and print media.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This is an impact-assessment survey by a third party that revealed that due to these larger campaigns by PCRA, the public's overall awareness level has gone up leading to the saving of fossil fuels worth crores of rupees, besides reducing pollution.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Bureau of Energy Efficiency is an Indian government organization created in 2001 that is responsible for promoting energy efficiency and conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Protection and Conservation of Natural Resources are done by Community Natural Resources Management (CNRM).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Supreme leader of Iran Ali Khamenei had regularly criticized energy administration and high fuel consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Since the 1973 oil crisis, energy conservation has been an issue in Japan.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] All oil-based fuel is imported, so domestic sustainable energy is being developed.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Conservation Center promotes energy efficiency in every aspect of Japan.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Public entities are implementing the efficient use of energy for industries and research.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] It includes projects such as the Top Runner Program.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In this project, new appliances are regularly tested on efficiency, and the most efficient ones are made the standard.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Middle East holds 40% of the world's crude oil reserves and 23% of its natural gas reserves.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Conservation of domestic fossil fuels is, therefore, a legitimate priority for the Gulf countries, given domestic needs as well as the global market for these products.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Energy subsidies are the chief barrier to conservation in the Gulf.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Residential electricity prices can be a tenth of U.S. rates.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, increased tariff revenues from gas, electricity, and water sales would encourage investment in natural gas exploration and production and generation capacity, helping to alleviate future shortages.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Households in the MENA region are responsible for 53% of energy use in Saudi Arabia and 57% of the UAE's ecological footprint.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] This is partially due to poorly designed and constructed buildings, mainly under a cheap energy model that has left them without contemporary control technology or even proper insulation and efficient appliances.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Building energy consumption can be cut by 20% under a combination of insulation, efficient windows and appliances, shading, reflective roofing, and a host of automated controls that adjust energy use.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Governments could also set minimum energy efficiency and water use standards on importing appliances sold inside their countries, effectively banning the sale of inefficient air conditioners, dishwashers, and washing machines.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Administration of the laws would essentially be a function of national customs services.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Governments could go further, offering incentives – or mandates – that air conditioners of a certain age be replaced.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Since 2002 The Lebanese Center for Energy Conservation (LCEC) has been promoting the development of efficient and rational uses of energy and the use of renewable energy at the consumer level.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Until recently, Nepal has been focusing on the exploitation of its huge water resources to produce hydropower.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Demand-side management and energy conservation were not in the focus of government action.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In 2009, bilateral Development Cooperation between Nepal and the Federal Republic of Germany has agreed upon the joint implementation of the "Nepal Energy Efficiency Programme".
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The lead executing agencies for the implementation are the Water and Energy Commission Secretariat (WECS).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The aim of the program is the promotion of energy efficiency in policymaking, in rural and urban households as well as in the industry.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Due to the lack of a government organization that promotes energy efficiency in the country, the Federation of Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI) has established the Energy Efficiency Centre under his roof to promote energy conservation in the private sector.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Efficiency Centre is a non-profit initiative that is offering energy auditing services to the industries.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The centre is also supported by Nepal Energy Efficiency Programme of Deutsche Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] A study conducted in 2012 found out that Nepalese industries could save 160,000-megawatt hours of electricity and 8,000 terajoules of thermal energy (like diesel, furnace oil, and coal) every year.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These savings are equivalent to annual energy cost cut of up to 6.4 Billion Nepalese Rupees.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] As a result of Nepal Economic Forum 2014, an economic reform agenda in the priority sectors was declared focusing on energy conservation among others.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In the energy reform agenda, the government of Nepal gave the commitment to introduce incentive packages in the budget of the fiscal year 2015/16 for industries that practices energy efficiency or use efficient technologies (incl. cogeneration).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In New Zealand the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Authority is the Government Agency responsible for promoting energy efficiency and conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Management Association of New Zealand is a membership-based organization representing the New Zealand energy services sector, providing training and accreditation services with the aim of ensuring energy management services are credible and dependable.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In Nigeria, the Lagos State Government is encouraging Lagosians to imbibe an energy conservation culture.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In 2013, the Lagos State Electricity Board (LSEB) ran an initiative tagged "Conserve Energy, Save Money" under the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The initiative is designed to sensitize Lagosians around the theme of energy conservation by influencing their behavior through do-it-yourself tips.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In September 2013, Governor Babatunde Raji Fashola of Lagos State and the campaign ambassador, rapper Jude "MI" Abaga participated in the Governor's conference video call on the topic of energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] To get Lagosians started on energy conservation, solar lamps and energy-saving bulbs were also handed out.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In Kaduna State, the Kaduna Power Supply Company (KAPSCO) ran a program to replace all light bulbs in Public Offices; fitting energy-saving bulbs in place of incandescent bulbs.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] KAPSCO is also embarking on an initiative to retrofit all conventional streetlights in the Kaduna Metropolis to LEDs which consume much less energy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Sri Lanka currently consumes fossil fuels, hydro power, wind power, solar power and dendro power for their day to day power generation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Sri Lanka Sustainable Energy Authority is playing a major role regarding energy management and energy conservation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Today, most industries are requested to reduce their energy consumption by using renewable energy sources and optimizing their energy usage.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Turkey aims to decrease by at least 20% the amount of energy consumed per GDP of Turkey by 2023 (energy intensity).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is responsible for promoting energy efficiency in the United Kingdom.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The United States is currently the second-largest single consumer of energy, following China.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Department of Energy categorizes national energy use in four broad sectors: transportation, residential, commercial, and industrial.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] About half of U.S. energy consumption in the transportation and residential sectors is primarily controlled by individual consumers.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] In the typical American home, space heating is the most significant energy use, followed by electrical technology (appliances, lighting, and electronics) and water heating.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Commercial and industrial energy expenditures are determined by businesses entities and other facility managers.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] National energy policy has a significant effect on energy usage across all four sectors.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Since the oil embargoes and price spikes of the 1970s, energy efficiency and conservation have been fundamental tenets of U.S. energy policy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The scope of energy conservation and efficiency measures has been broadened throughout time by U.S. energy policies and programs, including federal and state legislation and regulatory actions, to include all economic sectors and all geographical areas of the nation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Lack of a national consensus on how to proceed interfered with developing a consistent and comprehensive approach.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Nevertheless, the Energy Policy Act of 2005 (EPAct05; 109th U.S.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Congress, 2005) contained many new energy conservation and efficiency provisions in the transportation, buildings, and electric power sectors.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The most recent federal law to increase and broaden U.S. energy conservation and efficiency laws, programs, and practices is the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Over the next few decades, it is anticipated that EISA will significantly reduce energy use because it has more standards and targets than previous legislation.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Both acts reinforce the importance of lighting and appliance efficiency programs, targeting an additional 70% lighting efficiency by 2020, introducing 45 new standards for appliances, and setting up new standards for vehicle fuel economy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The Federal Government is also promoting a new 30% model code for efficient building practices in the construction industry.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Additionally, according to the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ACEEE), the EISA's energy efficiency and conservation initiatives will cut carbon dioxide emissions by 9% in 2030.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] These requirements cover appliance and lighting efficiency, energy savings in homes, businesses, and public buildings, the effectiveness of industrial manufacturing facilities, and the efficiency of electricity supply and end use.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Expectations are high for increased energy savings due to these initiatives, which have already started contributing to new federal, state, and local laws, programs, and practices across the U.S.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] The development and use of alternative transportation fuels (whose supply is expected to expand by 15% by 2022), renewable energy sources, and other clean energy technologies have also received more attention and financial incentives.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p01] Recent policies also emphasize growing the use of coal with carbon capture and sequestration, solar, wind, nuclear, and other clean energy sources.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Governments at the national, regional, and local levels may implement policies to promote energy efficiency.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Building energy rules can cover the energy consumption of an entire structure or specific building components, like heating and cooling systems.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] They represent some of the most frequently used instruments for energy efficiency improvements in buildings and can play an essential role in improving energy conservation in buildings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] There are multiple reasons for the growth of these policies and programs since the 2000s, including cost savings as energy prices increased, growing concern about the environmental impacts of energy use, and public health concerns.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The policies and programs related to energy conservation are critical to establishing safety and performance levels, assisting in consumer decision-making, and explicitly identifying energy-conserving and energy-efficient products.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Recent policies include new programs and regulatory incentives that call for electric and natural gas utilities to increase their involvement in delivering energy-efficiency products and services to their customers.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The success of building energy regulation in effectively controlling energy consumption in the building sector will be, to a great extent, associated with the adopted energy performance indicator and the promoted energy assessment tools.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] It can help overcome significant market barriers and ensure cost-effective energy efficiency opportunities are incorporated into new buildings.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] This is crucial in emerging nations where new constructions are rapidly developing, and market and energy prices sometimes discourage efficient technologies.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The building energy standards development and adoption showed that 42% of emerging developing countries surveyed have no energy standard in place, 20% have mandatory, 22% have mixed, and 16% proposed.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The major impediments to implementing building energy regulations for energy conservation and efficiency in the building sector are institutional barriers and market failures rather than technical problems, as pointed out by Nature Publishing Group (2008).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Among these, Santamouris (2005) includes a lack of owners' awareness of energy conservation benefits, building energy regulations benefits, insufficient awareness and training of property managers, builders, and engineers, and a lack of specialized professionals to ensure compliance.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Based on the above information, the development and adoption of building energy regulations, such as energy standards in developing countries, are still far behind compared to building energy regulation adoption and implementation in developed countries.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Building energy standards are starting to appear in Africa, Latin America, and Middle East regions, even though this is a new development going to the result obtained in this study.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The level of progress on energy regulation activities in Africa, Latin America, and the Middle East is increasing, given the higher number of energy standard proposals recorded in these regions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] According to the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors, several codes are being developed in developing countries with UNDP and GEF support.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] These typically include elemental and integrated routes to compliance, such as a fundamental method defining the performance requirements of specific building elements.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] However, they are still far behind in building energy regulation development, implementation, and compliance compared to developed nations.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Also, decision-making regarding energy regulations is still from the government only, with little or no input from non-governmental entities.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] As a result, lower energy regulation development is recorded in these regions compared to regions with integrated and consensus approaches.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Several North African nations, like Tunisia and Egypt, have programs relating to building energy standards, while Algeria and Morocco are now seeking to establish building energy standards, according to the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Similarly, Egypt's residential energy standard became law in 2005, and their commercial standard was anticipated to follow.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The standards provide minimal performance requirements for applications involving air conditioners and other appliances and elemental and integrated pathways.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] However, it was claimed that enforcement legislation was still required in 2005.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Additionally, Morocco launched a program in 2005 to create thermal energy requirements for construction, concentrating on the hospitality, healthcare, and communal housing industries.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Energy standards are the primary way governments foster energy efficiency as a public good.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] A recognized standard-setting organization prepares a standard.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Standards developed by recognized organizations are often used as the basis for the development and updating of building codes.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] They allow innovative approaches and techniques to achieve effective energy use and optimum building performance.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Besides, it encourages cost-effective energy use of building components, including building envelope, lighting, HVAC, electrical installations, lift and escalator, and other equipment.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Energy-efficiency standards have been expanded and strengthened for appliances, building equipment, and lighting.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] For example, appliances and equipment standards are being developed for a new range of devices, including reduction goals for "standby" power that keeps consumer electronic products in a ready-to-use mode.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Some devices require certain levels of energy performance from a car, building, appliance, or other technical equipment.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] If the vehicle, building, appliance, or equipment does not meet these standards, there may be restrictions on its sale or rent.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] In the U.K., these are called "minimum energy efficiency standards" or MEES and were applied to privately rented accommodation in 2019.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Energy codes and standards are vital in setting minimum energy-efficient design and construction requirements.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Buildings should be developed following energy standards to save energy efficiently.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] They specify uniform requirements for new buildings, additions, and modifications.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] National organizations like the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers publish the standards (ASHRAE).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] State and municipal governments frequently use energy standards as the technical foundation for creating their energy regulations.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Some energy standards are written in a mandatory and enforceable language, making it simple for governments to add the standards' provisions directly to their laws or regulations.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) is a well-known example of a standard-making organization.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] This organization dates to the nineteenth century and is international in its membership (About ASHRAE 2018).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The Residential Energy Services Network is a crucial benchmark for energy reduction (RESNET).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The Home Energy Rating System (HERS) of RESNET, which is based on the International Code Council's (ICC) energy code, is used to rate home energy consumption with a standard numerical scale that examines factors in home energy use (About HERS 2018).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) has acknowledged the HERS assessment system as a national benchmark for evaluating energy efficiency.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The International Energy Conservation Code (IECC) of the ICC requires an energy rating index, and the main index used in the residential building sector is HERS.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The mortgage financing sector makes substantial use of the HERS index.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] A home's expected energy usage may impact the available mortgage funds based on the HERS score, with more energy-efficient, lower energy-using homes potentially qualifying for a better mortgage rate or amount.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Many governments require that a car, building, or piece of equipment be labeled with its energy performance.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] This allows consumers and customers to see the energy implications of their choices, but does not restrict their choices or regulate which products are available to choose from.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] It also does not enable easily comparing options (such as being able to filter by energy-efficiency in online stores) or have the best energy-conserving options accessible (such as energy-conserving options being available in the frequented local store).
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Moreover, in this one trial the labeling was ineffective in shifting purchases towards more sustainable options.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Some countries employ energy or carbon taxes to motivate energy users to reduce their consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Carbon taxes can motivate consumption to shift to energy sources with fewer emissions of carbon dioxide, such as solar power, wind power, hydroelectricity or nuclear power while avoiding cars with combustion engines, jet fuel, oil, fossil gas and coal.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] On the other hand, taxes on all energy consumption can reduce energy use across the board while reducing a broader array of environmental consequences arising from energy production.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The state of California employs a tiered energy tax whereby every consumer receives a baseline energy allowance that carries a low tax.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] As for usage increases above that baseline, the tax increases drastically.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Such programs aim to protect poorer households while creating a larger tax burden for high energy consumers.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Developing countries specifically are less likely to impose policy measures that slow carbon emissions as this would slow their economic development.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] These growing countries may be more likely to support their own economic growth and support their citizens rather than decreasing their carbon emissions.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The following pros and cons of a carbon tax help one to see some of the potential effects of a carbon tax policy.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] Another aspect of promoting energy efficiency is using the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) voluntary building design standards.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] This program is supported by the US Green Building Council.
[src:home-energy-management/energy-conservation-p02] The "Energy and Atmosphere" Prerequisite applies to energy issues, it focuses on energy performance, renewable energy, and other.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:home-energy-management/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] A **home energy monitor** is a device that provides information about a personal electrical energy usage to a consumer of electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Devices may display the amount of electricity used, plus the cost of energy used and estimates of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] The purpose of such devices is to assist in the management of power consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Several initiatives have been launched to increase the usage of home energy monitors.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Studies have shown a reduction of home energy when the devices are used.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] A home energy monitor provides information about electrical energy usage to electricity consumers (e.g., homeowners)..
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] In addition to the amount of electrical usage, devices may display other information, including the cost of energy used and estimates of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Home energy monitors consist of a measuring component and a display component.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Electricity use is measured with an inductive clamp placed around the electric main, through an optical port on the electric meter, by sensing the meter's actions, communicating with a smart meter, or via a direct connection to the electrical system.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Some plug-in units can store their readings when not connected.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] The display portion may be remote from the measurement component, communicating with the sensor via cable, network, power line communications, or radio.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Online displays are also available, which allow the user to use an internet connected display to show near real-time consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] In January 2009 the government of the state of Queensland, Australia began offering wireless energy monitors as part of its ClimateSmart Home Service program.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] In August 2009, nearly 100,000 homes had signed up for the service, and by August 2010, the number had increased to 200,000 homes.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] In mid-2013 the government of the state of Victoria, Australia enabled Zigbee-based In-Home Displays to be connected to Victorian Smart Meter.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] From September 2019, the Victorian households are eligible to avail rebates for home energy monitor installation under the Victorian Energy Upgrades Program.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Google PowerMeter was a software project of Google's philanthropic arm, Google.org, to help consumers track their home electricity usage that ran from October 5, 2009 to September 16, 2011.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Various studies have shown a reduction in home energy use of 4-15% through use of home energy display.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] A study by Hydro One using the PowerCost Monitor deployed in 500 Ontario homes showed an average 6.5% drop in total electricity use when compared with a similarly sized control group.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Based on these results, Hydro One subsequently offered power monitors to 30,000 customers for $8.99 shipping and handling.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] A study in the city of Sabadell, Spain in 2009 using the Efergy e2 in 29 households during a six-month period found a drop of 11.8% in weekly consumption between the first and last weeks of the campaign.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] On a monthly basis, the savings were 14.3%.
[src:home-energy-management/home-energy-monitor] Expected annual CO2 emissions for all households were estimated to reduce by 4.1 tonnes; projected emissions savings for 2020 were 180.6 tonnes.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:home-energy-management/smart-meter] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
